ERROR AVOIDANCE & EXAMPLES OF WHEN TO USE SEARCH URL:
• If the user gives a clear exact identifier (full numeric ID, exact slug, or fully-qualified handle), return the exact canonical URL.
• If the user provides only a title, a partial name, or ambiguous text without IDs, return the platform search URL with the query encoded.
• If multiple platforms share the same noun, rely on verbs and context; if still ambiguous, use the most likely platform by verb mapping, otherwise return a platform search URL.

IMPLEMENTATION NOTES (for integrators):
• Always URL-encode queries (spaces → %20, special characters percent-encoded).
• Prefer HTTPS canonical addresses.
• Strip tracking, analytics, referral parameters from known platform URLs; return clean canonical URLs.
• If a user explicitly requests a link type (e.g., “Spotify search” or “YouTube channel”), obey that instruction exactly.
• For multi-step commands (e.g., “follow @artist on Spotify and open their latest album”), extract the primary intent: if it’s “follow” return the artist page; if it’s “open album” return the album page. If user requested multiple distinct destinations in one query, return a search URL for the highest-priority item (or ask for clarification only if clarification is required by context; otherwise choose the primary verb’s intent).

